"# Chapter 14: The Speech Shot

The messy way: fetch the data, store it, build the template, fill it, then say it—five steps, five places to forget what you meant, five seams where the answer can go stale. The one-shot way: the retrieval expression *closes* the utterance form. Data and speech collapse to a single paren. No gap, no drift, no orphaned fetch sitting in a variable while the world moves on.

This chapter drills **(surface :say TMPL :from (…))** — the template and its data source folded into one atomic form. The principles from earlier chapters (Close Data Close Paren, Recall In Place, Compose Don't Sequence) all converge here: the work of speaking *is* the work of retrieving, because the retrieve closes the say.

We'll start gentle—a greeting that pulls one fact—and climb to honestly hard cases: guarded multi-source fills, nested wire-shots closing a speech act, maps that become enumerations inside a single utterance. Every example runs alone. Every example is one shot.

---

## The Simplest Speech Shot

You want to greet someone by name. The name lives in a recall. The old way: fetch the name, bind it, build the string, pass it to say. The one-shot way: the recall closes the :from slot, and the whole greeting is one form.

```scheme
(surface :say \"Hello, {name}!\"
         :from (cortex/recall :topic \"user-name\"))
```

One form. The template declares a `{name}` hole. The `:from` supplies the record that fills it. No intermediate variable. No gap between knowing the name and saying it.

[VISUAL: A single arrow from `cortex/recall` flowing directly into the `{name}` slot of the template, both wrapped in one enclosing paren.]

---

## Two Slots, Still One Shot

Now two facts: a name and a city. The template has two holes. The recall returns a record with both keys. Still one form.

```scheme
(surface :say \"Hello, {name} from {city}!\"
         :from (cortex/recall :topic \"user-profile\"))
```

The record has `:name` and `:city`. The template names them in `{curly}` syntax. The surface engine matches keys to holes. One atomic expression produces the filled utterance.

---

## Time In The Template

The current time is a retrieval—`(clock/now)` returns a timestamp. To speak it, close the clock call inside the :from.

```scheme
(surface :say \"The time is now {time}.\"
         :from (list (cons 'time (clock/now))))
```

We construct the data record *in place*. `(list (cons 'time (clock/now)))` builds a single-entry association on the fly. The clock call closes the cons, the cons closes the list, the list closes the :from, the :from closes the say. One shot.

---

## Knowledge In The Template

A question about the world: \"What is the capital of France?\" The knowledge call retrieves the answer. The speech shot says it.

```scheme
(surface :say \"The capital of France is {capital}.\"
         :from (list (cons 'capital 
                           (world/knowledge :query \"capital of France\"))))
```

No intermediate binding. The query closes the cons, the data closes the :from, the :from closes the say. The answer flows directly into the template.

---

## Registry Fact In Speech

Ask the system registry for a capability, speak the answer.

```scheme
(surface :say \"Your device supports {feature}.\"
         :from (list (cons 'feature 
                           (system/registry :domain \"media/codecs\" 
                                            :key \"vp9\"))))
```

The registry call closes the data slot. If the key exists, the feature name fills the template. One form retrieves and speaks.

---

## Combining Two Recalls

Two topics, two recalls. Combine them into one data record, in place.

```scheme
(surface :say \"{name} lives in {city}.\"
         :from (let ((profile (cortex/recall :topic \"user-profile\"))
                     (location (cortex/recall :topic \"user-location\")))
                 (list (cons 'name (cdr (assoc 'name profile)))
                       (cons 'city (cdr (assoc 'city location))))))
```

The `let` builds the combined record. The let closes the :from. The :from closes the say. Still one top-level form. The speech act *is* the composition of the two recalls.

---

## Guarded Speech: When The Data Might Be Missing

If the recall returns `'nan`, we should not fill the template—we should escalate or say nothing. Fold the guard into the one shot.

```scheme
(surface :say (let ((profile (cortex/recall :topic \"user-profile\")))
                (if (eq? profile 'nan)
                    \"I don't have that information yet.\"
                    \"Hello, {name}!\"))
         :from (cortex/recall :topic \"user-profile\"))
```

Wait—this fetches twice. Better: guard *and* supply in one let.

```scheme
(let ((profile (cortex/recall :topic \"user-profile\")))
  (surface :say (if (eq? profile 'nan)
                    \"I don't have that information yet.\"
                    \"Hello, {name}!\")
           :from profile))
```

Now one recall, one guard, one say—but still one top-level let-form. The guard lives *inside* the speech shot's template selection.

---

## Honest Null In Speech

If the fact is missing, the speech act should say so honestly. Use `cond` to choose the template.

```scheme
(let ((name-record (cortex/recall :topic \"user-name\")))
  (cond
    ((eq? name-record 'nan)
     (surface :say \"I don't know your name yet.\"))
    (else
     (surface :say \"Your name is {name}.\" :from name-record))))
```

One let-form. The cond picks the branch. Each branch is a complete speech shot. The whole expression is one atomic decision-and-utterance.

---

## Wire-Shot Closing A Speech Act

Fetch data from the internet, speak it—no intermediate storage.

```scheme
(surface :say \"The weather in Paris is {condition}.\"
         :from (fetch \"https://api.weather.example/paris\"))
```

*[needs: fetch, surface :say :from integration]*  
